Definition of equilibrium potential describe the membrane potential which can perfectly offset the driving force caused by chemical potential
- At equilibrium, the difference of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Potential Energy > Electrochemical potential" data-href="Potential Energy#Electrochemical potential" href="cellular-neurobiology/membrane-biophysics/potential-energy.html#Electrochemical potential" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">electric potential</a> equals the difference of <a data-tooltip-position="top" aria-label="Potential Energy > Chemical Potential of Solutes" data-href="Potential Energy#Chemical Potential of Solutes" href="cellular-neurobiology/membrane-biophysics/potential-energy.html#Chemical Potential of Solutes" class="internal-link" target="_self" rel="noopener nofollow">chemical potential</a>
- the electrochemical potential outside equals inside of the cell<br>
<img alt="Pasted image 20250907181726.png" src="cellular-neurobiology/image/pasted-image-20250907181726.png" target="_self"> calculate the equilibrium potential for an ion \end{aligned} \\begin{aligned}
E{X} &amp;= \frac{RT}{zF}\ln\frac{[X]{out}}{[X]{in}} \
E{X} &amp;= \frac{61.5}{z}\log\frac{[X]{out}}{[X]{in}}
\end{aligned}
